---

<AcademyLayout title="What We Discovered">
  
  <Breadcrumbs partTitle="PART V: Findings" chapterTitle="What We Discovered" />

  <h1>What We Discovered</h1>

  <Prerequisites 
    difficulty="Research" 
    links={[
      { title: "Measuring Attention", url: "/attentionheadgenome/academy/part3-math-foundations" },
      { title: "The Four Head Species", url: "/attentionheadgenome/academy/part4-head-species" }
    ]}
  />

  <div class="lead">
    Using the mathematical tools from Part III, we analyzed the taxonomy from Part IV across 1,568 attention heads. The results uncovered three fundamental laws of transformer architecture.
  </div>

  <h2>Finding 1: The V/Q Spatial Scaling Law</h2>

  <WhyCare>
    If you know exactly where a head is located in the network depth, you can predict its V/Q Ratio. If you know its V/Q Ratio, you can predict its functional species. This proves that attention head formation is mathematically predictable, not random.
  </WhyCare>

  <p>
    <strong>Question:</strong> Does head geometry change with depth?
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Experiment:</strong> We plotted the V/Q Frobenius norm ratio ($||W_V||_F / ||W_Q||_F$) of every head against its normalized layer depth ($0$ to $1$).
  </p>
  
  <div class="code-block" style="color: var(--text-2);">
    # Result across all models<br>
    Llama-3.2-1B:  r = 0.812 (p < 1e-50)<br>
    Qwen-1.5B:     r = 0.865 (p < 1e-50)<br>
    Qwen-0.5B:     r = 0.803 (p < 1e-50)<br>
    GPT-2:         r = 0.771 (p < 1e-50)
  </div>

  <p>
    <strong>Interpretation:</strong> The ratio rises monotonically. Early layers have massive Query matrices (specializing in searching/routing). Late layers have massive Value matrices (specializing in payload delivery).
  </p>

  <Misconception>
    <Fragment slot="myth">The V/Q scaling law happens because later layers process more complex human language.</Fragment>
    <Fragment slot="truth">No. In Part VII, we show that the exact same V/Q scaling law emerges when training on gibberish or non-English data. It is a geometric property of the transformer architecture, not a property of language.</Fragment>
  </Misconception>

  <h2>Finding 2: The Bifurcation Axis</h2>

  <p>
    <strong>Question:</strong> How do heads choose their species during training?
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Experiment:</strong> We tracked the development of Sink, Local, Retrieval, and Induction heads across network depth.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Result:</strong> Early in the network (Layers 0–5), almost all heads are Local heads. Around 40–60% depth, the developmental manifold splits. A minority of heads violently break away from the Local cluster to become highly specialized Retrieval and Induction heads.
  </p>

  <h2>Finding 3: Circuit Co-Gating (The 96.5% Rule)</h2>

  <p>
    <strong>Question:</strong> Do Retrieval heads and Induction heads work independently?
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Experiment:</strong> We ran causal ablations. We deleted Retrieval heads and measured performance. We deleted Induction heads and measured performance. We deleted both and measured performance.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Result:</strong> Ablating Retrieval heads alone caused 0% recovery in long-context tasks. Ablating Induction heads alone caused 0% recovery. 
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Interpretation:</strong> They form a strict co-dependent pipeline. Retrieval heads find the needle. Induction heads extract it. If either pipeline breaks, the entire circuit fails. However, when we ablate <em>both</em> together, the model is able to bypass the broken circuit entirely, yielding a <strong>96.5% recovery</strong>.
  </p>

  <CouldBeWrong>
    <p>We claim Retrieval and Induction heads form a co-dependent pipeline.</p>
    <p><strong>Alternative Explanation:</strong> Redundancy masks the true pathway. Perhaps when you ablate one head, a backup circuit takes over, and the 0% recovery is actually an artifact of how we constructed the ablation benchmark.</p>
    <p><strong>Experiment to verify:</strong> Perform strict Activation Patching (causal scrubbing) to intervene directly on the residual stream, rather than full head ablation.</p>
  </CouldBeWrong>

  <InterviewQuestions title="Research Defense & Discussion">
    <details>
      <summary>Why didn't you use KL Divergence instead of Entropy?</summary>
      <div>
        KL Divergence measures the difference between two distributions (e.g., $P || Q$). Our task wasn't to compare a head to a baseline distribution, but to measure the absolute shape (focus vs. diffusion) of the single distribution $P$. Entropy is the mathematically correct tool for this single-distribution measurement.
      </div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>How can you be sure the V/Q Law isn't just weight decay artifact?</summary>
      <div>
        We tested an untrained, randomly initialized GPT-2 control model. The control model exhibited absolutely zero V/Q structure (r = 0.04). The structure only emerges through active gradient descent.
      </div>
    </details>
  </InterviewQuestions>

